1
00:03:19,449 --> 00:03:20,700
Hello.

2
00:03:21,660 --> 00:03:24,328
My name's Forrest. Forrest Gump.

3
00:03:29,877 --> 00:03:31,919
Do you want a chocolate?

4
00:03:34,506 --> 00:03:37,925
I could eat about
a million and a half of these.

5
00:03:39,094 --> 00:03:44,307
My mama always said
life was like a box of chocolates.

6
00:03:46,310 --> 00:03:49,186
You never know what you're gonna get.

7
00:03:56,403 --> 00:03:58,946
Those must be comfortable shoes.

8
00:04:00,324 --> 00:04:04,994
I'll bet you could walk all day
in shoes like that and not feel a thing.

9
00:04:07,205 --> 00:04:09,665
I wish I had shoes like that.

10
00:04:10,334 --> 00:04:11,876
My feet hurt.

11
00:04:13,086 --> 00:04:14,754
Mama always said there's an awful lot

12
00:04:14,838 --> 00:04:18,049
you could tell about a person
by their shoes:

13
00:04:19,176 --> 00:04:22,136
where they're going,
where they've been.

14
00:04:29,394 --> 00:04:31,437
I've worn lots of shoes.

15
00:04:34,566 --> 00:04:39,362
I bet if I think about it real hard,
I could remember my first pair of shoes.

16
00:04:42,282 --> 00:04:44,909
Mama said they'd take me anywhere.

17
00:04:45,702 --> 00:04:48,329
She said they was my magic shoes.

18
00:04:48,413 --> 00:04:51,582
All right, Forrest,
you can open your eyes now.

19
00:04:58,882 --> 00:05:01,342
Let's take a little walk around.

20
00:05:08,141 --> 00:05:09,934
How do those feel?

21
00:05:12,896 --> 00:05:15,064
His legs are strong, Mrs. Gump,

22
00:05:15,148 --> 00:05:17,650
as strong as I've ever seen,

23
00:05:17,734 --> 00:05:21,112
but his back is as crooked
as a politician.

24
00:05:22,406 --> 00:05:25,491
But we're gonna straighten him right up,
now, aren't we, Forrest?

25
00:05:25,575 --> 00:05:26,701
Forrest!

26
00:05:28,203 --> 00:05:29,412
Now, when I was a baby,

27
00:05:29,496 --> 00:05:32,331
Mama named me after
the great Civil War hero,

28
00:05:32,416 --> 00:05:34,834
General Nathan Bedford Forrest.

29
00:05:34,918 --> 00:05:37,128
She said we was related to him
in some way.

30
00:05:37,212 --> 00:05:38,587
And what he did was,

31
00:05:38,672 --> 00:05:42,925
he started up this club called
the Ku Klux Klan.

32
00:05:43,010 --> 00:05:46,345
They'd all dress up in their robes
and their bed sheets

33
00:05:46,430 --> 00:05:50,766
and act like a bunch of ghosts
or spooks or something.

34
00:05:50,851 --> 00:05:54,729
They'd even put bed sheets
on their horses and ride around.

35
00:05:54,813 --> 00:05:57,857
And anyway, that's how I got my name,

36
00:05:57,941 --> 00:05:59,358
Forrest Gump.

37
00:05:59,443 --> 00:06:01,193
Mama said that the "Forrest" part

38
00:06:01,278 --> 00:06:04,822
was to remind me that sometimes
we all do things that,

39
00:06:04,906 --> 00:06:07,700
well, just don't make no sense.

40
00:06:13,373 --> 00:06:16,876
Okay... Get it, get it...

41
00:06:16,960 --> 00:06:19,920
Wait, is it this way? Hold on.

42
00:06:20,839 --> 00:06:22,339
All right...

43
00:06:22,924 --> 00:06:24,592
What are you all staring at?

44
00:06:24,676 --> 00:06:29,138
Haven't you ever seen a little boy
with braces on his legs before?

45
00:06:30,682 --> 00:06:34,393
Don't ever let anybody tell you
they're better than you, Forrest.

46
00:06:34,478 --> 00:06:37,063
lf God intended
everybody to be the same,

47
00:06:37,147 --> 00:06:39,273
he'd have given us all braces
on our legs.

48
00:06:39,357 --> 00:06:43,152
Mama always had a way of explaining
things so I could understand them.

49
00:06:44,613 --> 00:06:48,115
We lived about a quarter mile
off Route 17,

50
00:06:48,200 --> 00:06:51,243
about a half mile from
the town of Greenbow, Alabama.

51
00:06:51,328 --> 00:06:54,080
That's in the county of Greenbow.

52
00:06:54,164 --> 00:06:58,584
Our house had been in Mama's family
since her grandpa's grandpa's grandpa

53
00:06:58,668 --> 00:07:00,586
had come across the ocean
about 1,000 years ago,

54
00:07:00,670 --> 00:07:02,588
something like that.

55
00:07:02,672 --> 00:07:05,382
Since it was just me and Mama
and we had all these empty rooms,

56
00:07:05,467 --> 00:07:08,219
Mama decided to let those rooms out,

57
00:07:08,303 --> 00:07:10,262
mostly to people passing through,

58
00:07:10,347 --> 00:07:14,308
like from, oh, Mobile,
Montgomery, places like that.

59
00:07:14,392 --> 00:07:17,103
That's how me and Mama got money.

60
00:07:17,187 --> 00:07:19,939
Mama was a real smart lady.

61
00:07:20,023 --> 00:07:25,027
Remember what I told you, Forrest.
You're no different than anybody else is.

62
00:07:27,531 --> 00:07:29,907
Did you hear what I said, Forrest?

63
00:07:29,991 --> 00:07:34,161
You're the same as everybody else.
You are no different.

64
00:07:34,663 --> 00:07:39,125
Your boy's different, Mrs. Gump.

65
00:07:39,209 --> 00:07:41,418
Now, his IQ is 75.

66
00:07:42,212 --> 00:07:45,339
Well, we're all different, Mr. Hancock.

67
00:07:48,927 --> 00:07:50,970
She wanted me to have
the finest education,

68
00:07:51,054 --> 00:07:54,974
so she took me to
the Greenbow County Central School.

69
00:07:55,058 --> 00:07:57,309
I met the principal and all.

70
00:07:57,811 --> 00:08:00,688
I want to show you something,
Mrs. Gump.

71
00:08:01,148 --> 00:08:04,024
Now, this is normal.

72
00:08:04,526 --> 00:08:07,820
Forrest is right here.

73
