I didn't know I was supposed to be
looking for him, sir.

985
01:17:38,571 --> 01:17:41,948
That's all these cripples,
down at the VA,

986
01:17:42,033 --> 01:17:44,451
that's all they ever talk about.

987
01:17:45,619 --> 01:17:48,580
Jesus this and Jesus that.

988
01:17:50,041 --> 01:17:52,334
Have I found Jesus?

989
01:17:52,960 --> 01:17:55,962
They even had a priest come
and talk to me.

990
01:17:56,839 --> 01:18:01,509
He said God is listening,
but I have to help myself.

991
01:18:02,887 --> 01:18:05,180
How if I accept Jesus into my heart,

992
01:18:06,182 --> 01:18:09,976
I'll get to walk beside him
in the kingdom of heaven.

993
01:18:10,061 --> 01:18:12,228
Did you hear what I said?

994
01:18:13,272 --> 01:18:17,275
Walk beside him
in the kingdom of heaven.

995
01:18:17,360 --> 01:18:20,320
Well, kiss my crippled ass.

996
01:18:20,404 --> 01:18:23,782
God is listening? What a crock of shit.

997
01:18:27,453 --> 01:18:30,080
I'm going to heaven, Lieutenant Dan.

998
01:18:31,999 --> 01:18:33,041
Oh?

999
01:18:37,880 --> 01:18:39,255
Well,

1000
01:18:42,218 --> 01:18:45,595
before you go, why don't you get
your ass down to the corner

1001
01:18:45,679 --> 01:18:48,181
-and get us another bottle of Ripple.
-Yes, sir.

1002
01:18:48,265 --> 01:18:53,395
We are at approximately 45th Street
in New York City at One Astor Plaza.

1003
01:18:53,479 --> 01:18:55,313
This is the site of the old Astor Hotel.

1004
01:18:55,398 --> 01:18:57,607
What the hell is in Bayou La Batre?

1005
01:18:57,691 --> 01:19:00,026
-Shrimping boats.
-Shrimping boats?

1006
01:19:00,111 --> 01:19:02,529
Who gives a shit
about shrimping boats?

1007
01:19:02,613 --> 01:19:04,072
I gotta buy me
one of them shrimping boats,

1008
01:19:04,156 --> 01:19:05,698
soon as I have some money.

1009
01:19:05,783 --> 01:19:08,618
I made me a promise to Bubba
in Vietnam

1010
01:19:08,702 --> 01:19:11,413
that as soon as the war was over,
we'd go in partners.

1011
01:19:11,497 --> 01:19:14,916
He'd be the captain of the
shrimping boat and I'd be his first mate.

1012
01:19:15,000 --> 01:19:18,461
But now that he's dead,
that means I gotta be the captain.

1013
01:19:18,546 --> 01:19:21,256
-A shrimp boat captain.
-Yes, sir.

1014
01:19:21,340 --> 01:19:24,092
A promise is a promise, Lieutenant Dan.

1015
01:19:25,594 --> 01:19:28,054
Now hear this!

1016
01:19:28,806 --> 01:19:32,642
Private Gump here
is gonna be a shrimp boat captain.

1017
01:19:33,394 --> 01:19:34,811
Well, I tell you what, Gilligan,

1018
01:19:34,895 --> 01:19:37,355
the day that you are
a shrimp boat captain,

1019
01:19:37,440 --> 01:19:40,984
-I will come and be your first mate.
-Okay.

1020
01:19:41,068 --> 01:19:45,405
lf you're ever a shrimp boat captain,
that's the day I'm an astronaut.

1021
01:19:45,489 --> 01:19:48,491
Danny, what are
you complaining about?

1022
01:19:48,576 --> 01:19:51,161
-What are you doing, hon?
-Mr. Hot Wheels.

1023
01:19:51,245 --> 01:19:54,873
-Who's your friend?
-My name is Forrest, Forrest Gump.

1024
01:19:55,708 --> 01:19:59,919
This is Cunning Carla
and Long-Limbs Lenore.

1025
01:20:01,005 --> 01:20:04,215
So, where you been, baby cakes, huh?
Haven't seen you around lately.

1026
01:20:04,300 --> 01:20:05,758
You know, you should have
been here for Christmas,

1027
01:20:05,843 --> 01:20:07,177
'cause Tommy bought a round
on the house

1028
01:20:07,261 --> 01:20:08,761
and gave everybody a turkey sandwich.

1029
01:20:08,846 --> 01:20:11,890
Well, well, I had company.

1030
01:20:12,766 --> 01:20:16,436
Hey, hey! We was just there.
That's at Times Square.

1031
01:20:17,062 --> 01:20:21,191
Don't you just love New Year's?
You get to start all over.

1032
01:20:21,275 --> 01:20:24,569
-Hey, Lenore...
-Everybody gets a second chance.

1033
01:20:24,653 --> 01:20:27,197
It's funny,
but in the middle of all that fun,

1034
01:20:27,281 --> 01:20:29,574
I began to think about Jenny,

1035
01:20:30,493 --> 01:20:34,954
wondering how she was spending
her New Year's night out in California.

1036
01:20:57,561 --> 01:21:01,064
...eight, seven, six, five,

1037
01:21:01,190 --> 01:21:04,651
four, three, two, one!

1038
01:21:04,777 --> 01:21:07,445
Happy New Year!

1039
01:21:23,921 --> 01:21:26,631
Happy New Year, Lieutenant Dan!

1040
01:22:01,917 --> 01:22:05,587
What are you, stupid or something?
What's your problem?

1041
01:22:06,255 --> 01:22:07,672
What's his problem?

1042
01:22:07,756 --> 01:22:10,008
Did you lose your pecker in the war
or something?

1043
01:22:10,092 --> 01:22:12,135
What, is your friend stupid
or something?

1044
01:22:12,219 --> 01:22:13,303
What did you say?

1045
01:22:13,387 --> 01:22:14,804
I said, is your friend stupid
or something?

1046
01:22:14,888 --> 01:22:17,056
Hey! Don't call him stupid!

1047
01:22:17,141 --> 01:22:19,100
-Hey, don't you push her!
-You shut up!

1048
01:22:19,184 --> 01:22:21,227
-Don't you ever call him stupid!
-What's the matter, baby?

1049
01:22:21,312 --> 01:22:23,021
-Why are you so upset?
-Just get the hell out of here.

1050
01:22:23,105 --> 01:22:24,188
-Stupid damn...
-Get your goddamn clothes...

1051
01:22:24,273 --> 01:22:25,773
You belong in Ripley's Believe It Or Not!

1052
01:22:25,858 --> 01:22:27,734
-Get the hell out of here!
-You should be in a sideshow!

1053
01:22:27,818 --> 01:22:28,860
Go on! Get out of here!

1054
01:22:28,944 --> 01:22:30,236
Come on, Lenore.
We don't need this shit!

1055
01:22:30,321 --> 01:22:31,696
Get out of here!

1056
01:22:33,324 --> 01:22:35,867
-You retard.
-Loser. You freak.

1057
01:22:41,248 --> 01:22:42,457
No, no.

1058
01:23:07,608 --> 01:23:11,569
I'm sorry I ruined your
New Year's Eve party, Lieutenant Dan.

1059
01:23:12,154 --> 01:23:14,447
She tasted like cigarettes.

1060
01:23:30,631 --> 01:23:35,134
I guess Lieutenant Dan figured there's
some things you just can't change.

1061
01:23:35,219 --> 01:23:40,348
He didn't want to be called crippled,
just like I didn't want to be called stupid.

1062
01:23:45,854 --> 01:23:47,730
Happy New Year, Gump.

1063
01:23:52,528 --> 01:23:53,903
The US Ping-Pong team

1064
01:23:53,987 --> 01:23:56,280
met with President Nixon today
at an Oval Office ceremony...

1065
01:23:56,365 --> 01:23:59,117
And wouldn't you know it?
A few months later,

1066
01:23:59,201 --> 01:24:03,162
they invited me and the Ping-Pong team
to visit the White House.

1067
01:24:03,247 --> 01:24:05,498
So, I went, again.

1068
01:24:06,333 --> 01:24:09,794
And I met the President
of the United States, again.

1069
01:24:10,546 --> 01:24:13,506
Only, this time, they didn't get us rooms
in a real fancy hotel.

1070
01:24:13,590 --> 01:24:16,968
So, are you enjoying yourself
in our nation's capital, young man?

1071
01:24:17,052 --> 01:24:20,054
-Yes, sir.
-Well, where are you staying?

1072
01:24:20,139 --> 01:24:22,765
-It's called the Hotel Ebbott.
-Oh, no, no, no, no.

1073
01:24:22,850 --> 01:24:25,977
I know of a much nicer hotel.
It's brand-new, very modern.

1074
01:24:26,061 --> 01:24:28,062
I'll have my people
take care of it for you.

1075
01:24:28,689 --> 01:24:29,814
Security, Frank Wills.

1076
01:24:29,898 --> 01:24:33,484
Yeah, sir, you might want
to send a maintenance man

1077
01:24:33,569 --> 01:24:36,237
over to that office across the way.

1078
01:24:36,321 --> 01:24:39,198
The lights are off, and they must be
looking for a fuse box or something,

1079
01:24:39,283 --> 01:24:41,993
'cause them flashlights,
they're keeping me awake.

1080
01:24:42,077 --> 01:24:43,703
Okay, sir. I'll check it out.

1081
01:24:43,787 --> 01:24:45,496
-Thank you.
-No problem.

1082
01:24:45,581 --> 01:24:47,498
-Good night.
-Good night.

1083
01:24:51,128 --> 01:24:56,507
Therefore, I shall resign the presidency
effective at noon tomorrow.

1084
01:24:56,592 --> 01:24:58,634
Vice President Ford

1085
01:24:58,719 --> 01:25:03,222
will be sworn in as president
at that hour in this office.

1086
01:25:04,600 --> 01:25:09,395
As I recall the high hopes for America
with which we began this second term...

1087
01:25:14,651 --> 01:25:16,194
Sergeant Gump.

1088
01:25:16,695 --> 01:25:18,905
-Yes, sir!
-As you were.

1089
01:25:18,989 --> 01:25:22,116
I have your discharge papers.
Your service is up, son.

1090
01:25:25,537 --> 01:25:28,289
Does this mean
I can't play Ping-Pong no more?

1091
01:25:28,373 --> 01:25:30,333
For the Army it does.

1092
01:25:32,961 --> 01:25:37,840
And just like that, my service
in the United States Army was over.

1093
01:25:43,138 --> 01:25:44,931
So, I went home.

1094
01:26:06,411 --> 01:26:09,831
-I'm home, Mama.
-I know, I know.

1095
01:26:11,458 --> 01:26:13,000
-Louise, he's here.
-Now, when I got home,

1096
01:26:13,085 --> 01:26:17,129
I had no idea,
but Mama had had all sorts of visitors.

1097
01:26:17,256 --> 01:26:19,549
We've had all sorts of visitors, Forrest.

1098
01:26:19,633 --> 01:26:22,718
Everybody wants you
to use their Ping-Pong stuff.

1099
01:26:22,803 --> 01:26:26,597
One man even left a check for $25,000

1100
01:26:26,682 --> 01:26:30,142
if you'd be agreeable to saying
you liked using their paddle.

1101
01:26:30,269 --> 01:26:32,937
Oh, but, Mama,
I only like using my own paddle.

1102
01:26:33,021 --> 01:26:35,022
-Hi, Miss Louise.
-Hey, Forrest.

1103
01:26:35,107 --> 01:26:38,025
I know that. I know that.

1104
01:26:38,110 --> 01:26:40,778
But it's $25,000, Forrest.

1105
01:26:40,863 --> 01:26:45,533
I thought maybe you could hold it
for a while, see if it grows on you.

1106
01:26:45,617 --> 01:26:47,743
-Oh, you look good, Forrest.
-That Mama, she sure was right.

1107
01:26:47,828 --> 01:26:50,329
-You look real good.
-It's funny how things work out.

1108
01:26:50,455 --> 01:26:53,583
I didn't stay home for long,
because I'd made a promise to Bubba,

1109
01:26:53,667 --> 01:26:55,918
and I always try to keep my promise.

1110
01:26:56,003 --> 01:26:57,545
So, I went on down to Bayou La Batre

1111
01:26:57,629 --> 01:27:01,382
to meet Bubba's family
and make their introduction.

1112
01:27:01,466 --> 01:27:05,136
Are you crazy, or just plain stupid?

1113
01:27:05,846 --> 01:27:08,097
Stupid is as stupid does, Mrs. Blue.

1114
01:27:08,181 --> 01:27:09,557
I guess.

1115
01:27:10,559 --> 01:27:14,145
And, of course,
I paid my respect to Bubba himself.

1116
01:27:16,148 --> 01:27:18,691
Hey, Bubba, it's me, Forrest Gump.

1117
01:27:21,820 --> 01:27:25,865
I remember everything you said,
and I got it all figured out.

1118
01:27:28,660 --> 01:27:35,458
I'm taking the $24,562
and 47 cents that I got...

1119
01:27:36,543 --> 01:27:40,129
Or, that's left after a new hair cut
and a new suit,

1120
01:27:40,213 --> 01:27:42,173
and I took Mama out
to a real fancy dinner,

1121
01:27:42,257 --> 01:27:45,509
and I bought a bus ticket
and three Dr. Peppers.

1122
01:27:46,053 --> 01:27:47,845
Tell me something.

1123
01:27:48,889 --> 01:27:51,015
Are you stupid or something?

1124
01:27:51,099 --> 01:27:53,142
Stupid is as stupid does, sir.

1125
01:27:53,226 --> 01:27:56,187
Well, that's what's left after me saying,

1126
01:27:57,105 --> 01:27:59,231
"When I was in China
on the All-America Ping-Pong team,

1127
01:27:59,358 --> 01:28:03,152
"I just loved playing Ping-Pong with
my Flex-O-Light Ping-Pong paddle,"

1128
01:28:03,236 --> 01:28:04,487
which everybody knows isn't true,

1129
01:28:04,571 --> 01:28:05,947
but Mama says it's just a little white lie

1130
01:28:06,031 --> 01:28:08,199
so it wouldn't hurt nobody.

1131
01:28:09,618 --> 01:28:15,539
So, anyway, I'm putting all that on gas,
ropes and new nets

1132
01:28:16,291 --> 01:28:18,042
and a brand-new shrimping boat.

1133
01:28:39,731 --> 01:28:42,984
Now, Bubba had told me everything
he knew about shrimping,

1134
01:28:43,068 --> 01:28:45,403
but you know what I found out?

1135
01:28:47,072 --> 01:28:49,407
Shrimping is tough.

1136
01:28:51,618 --> 01:28:53,452
I only caught five.

1137
01:28:53,578 --> 01:28:56,914
A couple more,
you could have yourself a cocktail.

1138
01:29:00,252 --> 01:29:02,003
Hey, you ever think
about naming this old boat?

1139
01:29:02,087 --> 01:29:04,755
It's bad luck
to have a boat without a name.

1140
01:29:07,134 --> 01:29:11,971
I'd never named a boat before,
but there was only one I could think of,

1141
01:29:13,140 --> 01:29:16,350
the most beautiful name
in the wide world.

1142
01:29:37,372 --> 01:29:40,207
Now, I hadn't heard from Jenny
in a long while,

1143
01:29:40,292 --> 01:29:42,835
but I thought about her a lot,

1144
01:29:42,961 --> 01:29:46,422
and I hoped that whatever
she was doing made her happy.

1145
01:31:32,696 --> 01:31:35,239
I thought about Jenny all the time.

1146
01:31:59,890 --> 01:32:01,056
Hey!

1147
01:32:24,915 --> 01:32:29,585
Lieutenant Dan,
what are you doing here?

1148
01:32:29,669 --> 01:32:33,589
Well, thought I'd try out my sea legs.

1149
01:32:33,673 --> 01:32:37,426
But you ain't got no legs,
Lieutenant Dan.

1150
01:32:37,510 --> 01:32:39,803
Yes, I know that.

1151
01:32:40,138 --> 01:32:42,181
You wrote me a letter, you idiot.

1152
01:32:42,307 --> 01:32:46,852
Well, well. Captain Forrest Gump.
I had to see this for myself.

1153
01:32:48,480 --> 01:32:55,361
And I told you if you were ever
a shrimp boat captain

1154
01:32:55,487 --> 01:32:58,072
that I'd be your first mate.
Well, here I am.

1155
01:32:58,156 --> 01:33:01,283
-I am a man of my word.
-Okay.

1156
01:33:01,368 --> 01:33:05,371
Yeah, but don't you be thinking that
I'm going to be calling you "sir."

1157
01:33:05,497 --> 01:33:06,830
No, sir.

1158
01:33:15,715 --> 01:33:18,008
That's my boat.

1159
01:33:20,595 --> 01:33:26,058
I have a feeling if we head due east,
we'll find some shrimp,

1160
01:33:26,184 --> 01:33:27,768
so take a left.

1161
01:33:29,187 --> 01:33:32,106
-Take a left!
-Which way?

1162
01:33:32,190 --> 01:33:34,858
Over there! They're over there!

1163
01:33:35,527 --> 01:33:39,363
-Get on the wheel and take a left!
-Okay.

1164
01:33:40,573 --> 01:33:44,702
Gump, what are you doing?
Take a left! Left!

1165
01:33:47,080 --> 01:33:50,708
That's where we're going
to find those shrimp, my boy!

1166
01:33:52,294 --> 01:33:53,877
That's where we'll find them.

1167
01:34:06,558 --> 01:34:10,686
-Still no shrimp, Lieutenant Dan.
-Okay, so I was wrong.

1168
01:34:11,396 --> 01:34:14,606
How are we going to find them?

1169
01:34:14,733 --> 01:34:17,234
Well, maybe you should
just pray for shrimp.

1170
01:34:23,867 --> 01:34:26,535
So, I went to church every Sunday.

1171
01:34:27,787 --> 01:34:29,788
Sometimes Lieutenant Dan came, too,

1172
01:34:29,914 --> 01:34:32,916
though I think
he left the praying up to me.

1173
01:34:48,391 --> 01:34:52,770
-No shrimp.
-Where the hell's this God of yours?

1174
01:34:53,605 --> 01:34:59,318
It's funny Lieutenant Dan said that,
'cause right then, God showed up.

1175
01:35:16,169 --> 01:35:21,006
-You'll never sink this boat!
-Now, me, I was scared,

1176
01:35:21,132 --> 01:35:24,176
but Lieutenant Dan, he was mad.

1177
01:35:24,302 --> 01:35:25,636
Come on!

1178
01:35:28,765 --> 01:35:33,977
You call this a storm?
Come on, you son of a bitch!

1179
01:35:36,106 --> 01:35:40,484
It's time for a showdown! You and me!

1180
01:35:40,610 --> 01:35:44,488
I'm right here! Come and get me!

1181
01:35:46,282 --> 01:35:50,160
You'll never sink this boat!

1182
01:35:52,205 --> 01:35:54,373
Hurricane Carmen
came through here yesterday,

1183
01:35:54,499 --> 01:35:57,042
destroying nearly everything in its path.

1184
01:35:57,168 --> 01:35:59,670
And as in other towns
up and down the coast,

1185
01:35:59,838 --> 01:36:02,214
Bayou La Batre's
entire shrimping industry

1186
01:36:02,298 --> 01:36:06,176
has fallen victim to Carmen
and has been left in utter ruin.

1187
01:36:06,302 --> 01:36:09,430
Speaking with local officials,
this reporter has learned,

1188
01:36:09,514 --> 01:36:12,975
in fact, only one shrimping boat
actually survived the storm.

1189
01:36:13,351 --> 01:36:15,978
Louise. Louise, there's Forrest.

1190
01:36:16,688 --> 01:36:18,689
After that, shrimping was easy.

1191
01:36:24,362 --> 01:36:27,489
Since people still needed
them shrimps for shrimp cocktails

1192
01:36:27,574 --> 01:36:31,702
and barbecues and all,
and we were the only boat left standing,

1193
01:36:31,870 --> 01:36:35,122
Bubba-Gump Shrimp's what they got.

1194
01:36:35,206 --> 01:36:39,793
We got a whole bunch of boats,
12 Jennys,

1195
01:36:39,878 --> 01:36:43,380
a big old warehouse. We even have
hats that say "Bubba-Gump" on them.

1196
01:36:43,715 --> 01:36:47,009
Bubba-Gump Shrimp.
It's a household name.

1197
01:36:47,218 --> 01:36:48,927
Hold on there, boy.

1198
01:36:49,053 --> 01:36:53,599
Are you telling me you're the owner of
the Bubba-Gump Shrimp Corporation?

1199
01:36:53,725 --> 01:36:56,727
Yes, sir. We got more money
than Davy Crockett.

1200
01:36:58,354 --> 01:37:02,399
Boy, I heard some whoppers in my time,
but that tops them all.

1201
01:37:05,111 --> 01:37:07,905
We was sitting next to a millionaire.

1202
01:37:11,409 --> 01:37:16,038
Well, I thought it was a very lovely story,

1203
01:37:16,456 --> 01:37:21,084
and you tell it so well,
with such enthusiasm.

1204
01:37:22,795 --> 01:37:25,464
Would you like to see
what Lieutenant Dan looks like?

1205
01:37:25,590 --> 01:37:27,090
Well, yes, I would.

1206
01:37:32,305 --> 01:37:34,348
That's him right there.

1207
01:37:36,476 --> 01:37:38,727
And let me tell you something
about Lieutenant Dan...

1208
01:37:39,896 --> 01:37:40,938
Forrest,

1209
01:37:46,486 --> 01:37:49,279
I never thanked you for saving my life.

1210
01:38:15,306 --> 01:38:21,603
He never actually said so,
but I think he made his peace with God.

1211
01:38:29,279 --> 01:38:31,488
For the second time in 17 days,

1212
01:38:31,614 --> 01:38:35,075
President Ford escaped
possible assassination today.

1213
01:38:35,159 --> 01:38:36,451
Base to Jenny 1.

1214
01:38:36,536 --> 01:38:40,038
-Base to Jenny 1.
-Jenny 1. Go, Margo.

1215
01:38:40,123 --> 01:38:41,623
Forrest has a phone call.

1216
01:38:41,708 --> 01:38:44,209
Yeah, well, you'll have to tell them
to call him back.

1217
01:38:44,294 --> 01:38:47,671
-He is indisposed at the moment.
-His mama's sick.

1218
01:39:08,359 --> 01:39:10,736
-Where's Mama?
-She's upstairs.

1219
01:39:13,573 --> 01:39:15,532
Hi, Forrest.

1220
01:39:16,492 --> 01:39:19,036
-I'll see you tomorrow.
-All right.

1221
01:39:25,710 --> 01:39:28,879
We sure got you straightened out,
didn't we, boy?

1222
01:39:40,224 --> 01:39:44,186
-What's the matter, Mama?
-I'm dying, Forrest.

1223
01:39:47,523 --> 01:39:49,900
Come on in, sit down over here.

1224
01:40:04,248 --> 01:40:07,751
-Why are you dying, Mama?
-It's my time.

1225
01:40:08,753 --> 01:40:10,629
It's just my time.

1226
01:40:12,090 --> 01:40:16,259
Now, don't you be afraid, sweetheart.

1227
01:40:17,887 --> 01:40:20,263
Death is just a part of life,

1228
01:40:21,265 --> 01:40:23,892
something we're all destined to do.

1229
01:40:25,728 --> 01:40:30,107
I didn't know it,
but I was destined to be your mama.

1230
01:40:30,942 --> 01:40:34,528
-I did the best I could.
-You did good, Mama.

1231
01:40:35,321 --> 01:40:40,492
Well, I happen to believe
you make your own destiny.

1232
01:40:41,994 --> 01:40:45,247
You have to do the best
with what God gave you.

1233
01:40:49,127 --> 01:40:51,253
What's my destiny, Mama?

1234
01:40:53,423 --> 01:40:56,633
You're going to have
to figure that out for yourself.

1235
01:40:57,927 --> 01:41:00,887
Life is a box of chocolates, Forrest.

1236
01:41:00,972 --> 01:41:03,140
You never know
what you're going to get.

1237
01:41:03,266 --> 01:41:07,644
Mama always had a way of explaining
things so I could understand them.

1238
01:41:07,729 --> 01:41:09,938
I will miss you, Forrest.

1239
01:41:11,774 --> 01:41:15,819
She had got the cancer
and died on a Tuesday.

1240
01:41:17,321 --> 01:41:20,657
I bought her a new hat
with little flowers on it.

1241
01:41:23,703 --> 01:41:26,997
And that's all I have to say about that.

1242
01:41:33,838 --> 01:41:36,131
Didn't you say you were waiting
for the number seven bus?

1243
01:41:36,215 --> 01:41:39,009
There'll be another one along shortly.

1244
01:41:42,847 --> 01:41:46,433
Now, because I had been a football star,
and a war hero,

1245
01:41:46,517 --> 01:41:49,644
and a national celebrity,
and a shrimping boat captain,

1246
01:41:50,146 --> 01:41:53,356
and a college graduate,
the city fathers of Greenbow, Alabama

1247
01:41:53,483 --> 01:41:56,693
decided to get together
and offered me a fine job.

1248
01:41:58,070 --> 01:42:01,740
So, I never went back to work
for Lieutenant Dan,

1249
01:42:01,866 --> 01:42:04,576
though he did take care
of my Bubba-Gump money.

1250
01:42:04,702 --> 01:42:09,289
He got me invested
in some kind of fruit company.

1251
01:42:09,373 --> 01:42:10,957
And so then, I got a call from him saying

1252
01:42:11,042 --> 01:42:14,503
we don't have to worry about money
no more, and I said,

1253
01:42:14,587 --> 01:42:16,880
"That's good. One less thing."

1254
01:42:19,926 --> 01:42:23,303
Now, Mama said there's only
so much fortune a man really needs,

1255
01:42:24,555 --> 01:42:27,432
and the rest is just for showing off.

1256
01:42:27,517 --> 01:42:31,394
So, I gave a whole bunch of it
to the Foursquare gospel church,

1257
01:42:34,065 --> 01:42:38,568
and I gave a whole bunch to the
Bayou La Batre fishing hospital.

1258
01:42:40,905 --> 01:42:45,450
And even though Bubba was dead
and Lieutenant Dan said I was nuts,

1259
01:42:45,576 --> 01:42:48,203
I gave Bubba's mama Bubba's share.

1260
01:42:52,416 --> 01:42:54,125
You know what?

1261
01:42:55,378 --> 01:42:58,380
She didn't have to work
in nobody's kitchen no more.

1262
01:42:58,464 --> 01:43:00,090
That smells wonderful.

1263
01:43:00,925 --> 01:43:04,845
And 'cause I was a gazillionaire
and I liked doing it so much,

1264
01:43:04,929 --> 01:43:07,264
I cut that grass for free.

1265
01:43:11,060 --> 01:43:13,937
But at night time
when there was nothing to do

1266
01:43:14,021 --> 01:43:16,398
and the house was all empty,

1267
01:43:17,400 --> 01:43:19,776
I'd always think of Jenny.

1268
01:44:23,466 --> 01:44:26,635
And then, she was there.

1269
01:44:59,627 --> 01:45:02,796
-Hello, Forrest.
-Hello, Jenny.

1270
01:45:14,350 --> 01:45:16,977
Jenny came back and stayed with me.

1271
01:45:18,562 --> 01:45:22,232
Maybe it was because
she had nowhere else to go,

1272
01:45:22,358 --> 01:45:26,069
or maybe it was because she was
so tired, 'cause she went to bed

1273
01:45:26,195 --> 01:45:30,156
and slept and slept,
like she hadn't slept in years.

1274
01:45:31,409 --> 01:45:33,702
It was wonderful having her home.

1275
01:45:35,037 --> 01:45:40,166
Every day we'd take a walk and
I'd jabber on like a monkey in a tree,

1276
01:45:40,251 --> 01:45:42,794
and she'd listen about Ping-Ponging,
and shrimping,

1277
01:45:42,878 --> 01:45:47,173
and Mama making a trip up to heaven.
I did all the talking.

1278
01:45:47,258 --> 01:45:50,593
Jenny most of the time was real quiet.

1279
01:46:30,760 --> 01:46:33,970
How could you do this?

1280
01:47:10,925 --> 01:47:14,260
Sometimes I guess there
just aren't enough rocks.

1281
01:47:16,472 --> 01:47:20,975
I never really knew why she came back,
but I didn't care.

1282
01:47:21,143 --> 01:47:25,438
It was like olden times.
We was like peas and carrots again.

1283
01:47:27,525 --> 01:47:31,861
Every day, I'd pick pretty flowers
and put them in her room for her,

1284
01:47:33,364 --> 01:47:36,950
and she gave me the best gift anyone
could ever get in the wide world.

1285
01:47:37,034 --> 01:47:39,869
-New shoes.
-They make them just for running.

1286
01:47:44,875 --> 01:47:48,169
And she even showed me
how to dance.

1287
01:47:56,345 --> 01:48:00,557
And, well, we was like family,
Jenny and me.

1288
01:48:04,311 --> 01:48:07,230
And it was the happiest time in my life.

1289
01:48:26,876 --> 01:48:28,668
...and this Fourth is witnessing
one of the

1290
01:48:28,752 --> 01:48:31,754
largest fireworks displays
in the nation's...

1291
01:48:31,839 --> 01:48:34,757
-You done watching it?
-...here in New York Harbor...

1292
01:48:34,884 --> 01:48:36,676
-I'm going to bed.
-...with a spectacular display

1293
01:48:36,760 --> 01:48:39,804
of tall ships earlier.
The Statue of Liberty...

1294
01:48:46,854 --> 01:48:48,855
Will you marry me?

1295
01:48:53,777 --> 01:48:56,738
I'd make a good husband, Jenny.

1296
01:48:59,408 --> 01:49:01,451
You would, Forrest.

1297
01:49:03,287 --> 01:49:05,622
But you won't marry me.

1298
01:49:07,917 --> 01:49:10,126
You don't want to marry me.

1299
01:49:13,714 --> 01:49:16,132
Why don't you love me, Jenny?

1300
01:49:21,138 --> 01:49:23,264
I'm not a smart man,

1301
01:49:24,975 --> 01:49:27,393
but I know what love is.

1302
01:50:04,431 --> 01:50:05,682
Jenny.

1303
01:50:07,601 --> 01:50:10,103
Forrest, I do love you.

1304
01:51:03,240 --> 01:51:06,909
-Where are you running off to?
-I'm not running.

1305
01:52:38,502 --> 01:52:43,840
That day, for no particular reason,
I decided to go for a little run.

1306
01:52:45,008 --> 01:52:49,429
So, I ran to the end of the road,
and when I got there,

1307
01:52:49,513 --> 01:52:51,264
I thought maybe I'd run
to the end of town.

1308
01:52:51,348 --> 01:52:54,600
President Carter, suffering from heat
exhaustion, fell into the arms of...

1309
01:52:54,685 --> 01:52:56,352
And when I got there,

1310
01:52:56,437 --> 01:53:00,606
I thought maybe I'd just
run across Greenbow County.

1311
01:53:00,691 --> 01:53:03,109
And I figured since I'd run this far,

1312
01:53:03,193 --> 01:53:06,446
maybe I'd just run across
the great state of Alabama.

1313
01:53:06,530 --> 01:53:07,738
And that's what I did.

1314
01:53:08,365 --> 01:53:10,158
I ran clear across Alabama.

1315
01:53:11,201 --> 01:53:14,370
For no particular reason,
I just kept on going.

1316
01:53:15,706 --> 01:53:17,290
I ran clear to the ocean.

1317
01:53:23,172 --> 01:53:26,340
And when I got there,
I figured since I'd gone this far,

1318
01:53:26,884 --> 01:53:29,719
might as well turn around
and just keep on going.

1319
01:53:33,474 --> 01:53:38,060
And when I got to another ocean,
I figured since I'd gone this far,

1320
01:53:39,855 --> 01:53:43,566
I might as well just turn back
and keep right on going.

1321
01:53:44,735 --> 01:53:49,572
When I got tired, I slept.
When I got hungry, I ate.

1322
01:53:49,656 --> 01:53:52,700
When I had to go, you know...

1323
01:53:54,328 --> 01:53:55,495
I went.

1324
01:53:55,579 --> 01:53:58,581
And so, you just ran.

1325
01:54:00,334 --> 01:54:01,417
Yeah.

1326
01:54:36,703 --> 01:54:41,958
I'd think a lot about Mama
and Bubba and Lieutenant Dan.

1327
01:54:42,960 --> 01:54:46,462
But most of all, I thought about Jenny.

1328
01:54:47,548 --> 01:54:49,715
I thought about her a lot.

1329
01:54:50,467 --> 01:54:53,553
For more than two years now,
a man named Forrest Gump,

1330
01:54:53,637 --> 01:54:57,056
a gardener from Greenbow, Alabama,
stopping only to sleep,

1331
01:54:57,140 --> 01:54:59,308
has been running across America.

1332
01:54:59,393 --> 01:55:01,394
Charles Cooper brings us this report.

1333
01:55:02,312 --> 01:55:04,730
For the fourth time
on his journey across America,

1334
01:55:04,815 --> 01:55:07,650
Forrest Gump,
the gardener from Greenbow, Alabama,

1335
01:55:07,776 --> 01:55:10,653
is about to cross
the Mississippi River again today.

1336
01:55:11,280 --> 01:55:13,322
-I'll be damned. Forrest?
-Sir, why are you running?

1337
01:55:13,407 --> 01:55:14,490
Why are you running?

1338
01:55:14,575 --> 01:55:16,158
Are you doing this for world peace?

1339
01:55:16,243 --> 01:55:17,577
Are you doing this for the homeless?

1340
01:55:17,661 --> 01:55:20,663
-Are you running for women's rights?
-Or for the environment?

1341
01:55:20,747 --> 01:55:21,747
Or for animals?

1342
01:55:21,832 --> 01:55:24,750
They just couldn't believe that
somebody would do all that running

1343
01:55:24,835 --> 01:55:26,210
for no particular reason.

1344
01:55:26,295 --> 01:55:28,254
Why are you doing this?

1345
01:55:28,338 --> 01:55:33,342
I just felt like running.

1346
01:55:33,468 --> 01:55:36,679
It's you. I can't believe it's really you.

1347
01:55:37,514 --> 01:55:42,643
Now, for some reason, what I was doing
seemed to make sense to people.

1348
01:55:42,811 --> 01:55:44,937
I mean, it was like an alarm
went off in my head, you know?

1349
01:55:45,022 --> 01:55:46,856
I said,
"Here's a guy that's got his act together.

1350
01:55:46,982 --> 01:55:48,941
"Here's somebody
who's got it all figured out.

1351
01:55:49,026 --> 01:55:53,112
"Here's somebody who has the answer."
I'll follow you anywhere, Mr. Gump.

1352
01:55:53,196 --> 01:55:55,031
So, I got company.

1353
01:55:56,867 --> 01:56:02,705
And after that, I got more company.
And then, even more people joined in.

1354
01:56:05,167 --> 01:56:08,377
Somebody later told me
it gave people hope.

1355
01:56:10,172 --> 01:56:13,549
Now... Now, I don't know
anything about that,

1356
01:56:14,384 --> 01:56:16,969
but some of those people
asked me if I could help them out.

1357
01:56:17,179 --> 01:56:20,431
Hey, man, hey, listen, I was wondering
if you might help me, huh?

1358
01:56:20,515 --> 01:56:22,266
Listen, I'm in the
bumper sticker business

1359
01:56:22,351 --> 01:56:24,101
and I've been trying
to think up a good slogan.

1360
01:56:24,186 --> 01:56:27,313
And since you have been such a big
inspiration to the people around here,

1361
01:56:27,397 --> 01:56:29,315
I thought you might
be able to help me jump into...

1362
01:56:29,399 --> 01:56:33,027
Whoa, man! You just ran through
a big pile of dog shit!

1363
01:56:34,571 --> 01:56:37,239
-It happens.
-What, shit?

1364
01:56:38,742 --> 01:56:40,701
Sometimes.

1365
01:56:42,579 --> 01:56:45,247
And some years later,
I heard that that fellow

1366
01:56:45,332 --> 01:56:46,957
did come up with
a bumper sticker slogan,

1367
01:56:47,042 --> 01:56:50,252
and he made a lot of money off of it.

1368
01:56:51,713 --> 01:56:53,923
Another time, I was running along,

1369
01:56:54,049 --> 01:56:57,343
somebody who had lost all his money
in the T-shirt business,

1370
01:56:57,427 --> 01:56:59,470
he wanted to put my face on a T-shirt,

1371
01:56:59,554 --> 01:57:02,515
but he couldn't draw that well,
and he didn't have a camera.

1372
01:57:02,599 --> 01:57:06,102
Here, use this one.
Nobody likes that color anyway.

1373
01:57:10,941 --> 01:57:12,608
Have a nice day.

1374
01:57:14,236 --> 01:57:15,361
Well, some years later,

1375
01:57:15,445 --> 01:57:19,365
I found out that that man
did come up with an idea for a T-shirt.

1376
01:57:19,449 --> 01:57:21,826
He made a lot of money off of it.

1377
01:57:24,621 --> 01:57:29,041
Anyway, like I was saying,
I had a lot of company.

1378
01:57:30,293 --> 01:57:31,460
My mama always said,

1379
01:57:31,545 --> 01:57:35,965
"You got to put the past behind you
before you can move on."

1380
01:57:37,634 --> 01:57:40,970
And I think that's what
my running was all about.

1381
01:57:41,805 --> 01:57:45,808
I had run for three years, two months,

1382
01:57:46,059 --> 01:57:48,394
14 days and 16 hours.

1383
01:58:04,077 --> 01:58:06,412
Quiet. Quiet.
He's going to say something.

1384
01:58:17,841 --> 01:58:19,592
I'm pretty tired.

1385
01:58:22,429 --> 01:58:24,472
Think I'll go home now.

1386
01:58:43,033 --> 01:58:45,493
Now what are we supposed to do?

1387
01:58:46,453 --> 01:58:50,706
And just like that,
my running days was over.

1388
01:58:52,667 --> 01:58:54,418
So, I went home to Alabama.

1389
01:58:55,212 --> 01:58:59,381
Moments ago, at 2:25 p.m.,
as President Reagan was leaving the...

1390
01:59:01,134 --> 01:59:05,304
...five or six gunshots were fired
by an unknown would-be assassin.

1391
01:59:05,806 --> 01:59:08,140
The President was shot in the chest,
and the assailant...

1392
01:59:08,225 --> 01:59:10,184
I picked up the mail.

1393
01:59:10,977 --> 01:59:14,814
And one day, out of the blue clear sky,
I got a letter from Jenny,

1394
01:59:14,898 --> 01:59:19,151
wondering if I could come down
to Savannah and see her,

1395
01:59:19,236 --> 01:59:21,821
and that's what I'm doing here.

1396
01:59:21,905 --> 01:59:24,490
She saw me on TV, running.

1397
01:59:24,574 --> 01:59:28,828
I'm supposed to go on the
number nine bus to Richmond Street

1398
01:59:28,912 --> 01:59:35,835
and get off and go one block left
to 1947 Henry Street, Apartment 4.

1399
01:59:35,919 --> 01:59:39,588
Why, you don't need to take a bus.

1400
01:59:39,714 --> 01:59:44,260
Henry Street is just five
or six blocks down that way.

1401
01:59:46,096 --> 01:59:48,430
-Down that way?
-Down that way.

1402
01:59:51,434 --> 01:59:53,352
It was nice talking to you.

1403
01:59:54,396 --> 01:59:57,022
I hope everything works out for you!

1404
02:00:04,781 --> 02:00:06,448
Hey!

1405
02:00:06,867 --> 02:00:08,534
Forrest!

1406
02:00:08,785 --> 02:00:12,037
How you doing? Come in, come in!

1407
02:00:12,122 --> 02:00:13,330
I got your letter.

1408
02:00:13,415 --> 02:00:16,041
I was wondering about that.

1409
02:00:17,586 --> 02:00:19,378
Is this your house?

1410
02:00:19,462 --> 02:00:22,548
Yeah. It's messy right now.
I just got off work.

1411
02:00:22,632 --> 02:00:26,343
It's nice. You got air conditioning.

1412
02:00:33,226 --> 02:00:35,269
-Thank you.
-I ate some.

1413
02:00:38,064 --> 02:00:43,485
Hey, I kept a scrapbook
of your clippings and everything.

1414
02:00:43,612 --> 02:00:45,237
There you are.

1415
02:00:46,990 --> 02:00:48,073
And this, I got you running.

1416
02:00:51,161 --> 02:00:53,329
I ran a long way,

1417
02:00:53,830 --> 02:00:55,664
for a long time.

1418
02:00:57,876 --> 02:00:59,376
And there...

1419
02:01:05,884 --> 02:01:09,345
Listen, Forrest,
I don't know how to say this.

1420
02:01:11,848 --> 02:01:16,185
I just I want to apologize
for anything that I ever did to you,

1421
02:01:16,311 --> 02:01:21,565
'cause I was messed up
for a long time, and...

1422
02:01:24,361 --> 02:01:25,986
-Hey.
-Hi.

1423
02:01:26,196 --> 02:01:27,196
Hey, you.

1424
02:01:28,365 --> 02:01:31,325
-This is an old friend from Alabama.
-How do you do?

1425
02:01:31,409 --> 02:01:34,495
Listen, next week my schedule changes,
so I'll be able to... But thanks...

1426
02:01:34,579 --> 02:01:36,622
No problem. Got to go, Jen,
I'm double-parked.

1427
02:01:36,706 --> 02:01:38,582
-Okay. Thanks.
-Bye.

1428
02:01:42,045 --> 02:01:44,797
This is my very good friend, Mr. Gump.
Can you say hi to him?

1429
02:01:44,881 --> 02:01:47,967
-Hello, Mr. Gump.
-Hello.

1430
02:01:48,051 --> 02:01:51,053
-Can I go watch TV now?
-Yes, you can. Just keep it low.

1431
02:01:53,890 --> 02:01:57,226
-You're a mama, Jenny.
-I'm a mama.

1432
02:02:00,105 --> 02:02:01,939
His name's Forrest.

1433
02:02:03,066 --> 02:02:04,400
Like me.

1434
02:02:06,027 --> 02:02:08,153
I named him after his daddy.

1435
02:02:09,114 --> 02:02:11,573
He got a daddy named Forrest, too?

1436
02:02:12,867 --> 02:02:14,910
You're his daddy, Forrest.

1437
02:02:29,384 --> 02:02:30,592
Hey.

1438
02:02:31,761 --> 02:02:34,638
Forrest, look at me.
Look at me, Forrest.

1439
02:02:37,225 --> 02:02:41,353
There's nothing you need to do, okay?
You didn't do anything wrong.

1440
02:02:41,896 --> 02:02:43,272
Okay?

1441
02:02:47,610 --> 02:02:49,486
Isn't he beautiful?

1442
02:02:50,488 --> 02:02:53,449
He's the most beautiful thing
I've ever seen.

1443
02:02:57,245 --> 02:02:58,328
But...

1444
02:03:02,000 --> 02:03:04,877
Is he smart, or...

1445
02:03:04,961 --> 02:03:08,964
He's very smart.
He's one of the smartest in his class.

1446
02:03:18,308 --> 02:03:20,768
Yeah, it's okay. Go talk to him.

1447
02:03:30,111 --> 02:03:32,946
-What are you watching?
-Bert and Ernie.

1448
02:03:56,054 --> 02:03:57,846
Forrest,

1449
02:03:59,307 --> 02:04:00,849
I'm sick.

1450
02:04:03,520 --> 02:04:07,147
What, do you have
a cough due to a cold?

1451
02:04:07,232 --> 02:04:09,608
I have some kind of virus,

1452
02:04:09,692 --> 02:04:12,402
and the doctors don't...
They don't know what it is,

1453
02:04:12,529 --> 02:04:15,531
and there isn't anything
they can do about it.

1454
02:04:19,911 --> 02:04:22,204
You could come home with me.

1455
02:04:23,873 --> 02:04:29,545
Jenny, you and little Forrest could
come stay at my house in Greenbow.

1456
02:04:33,883 --> 02:04:36,677
I'll take care of you if you're sick.

1457
02:04:39,055 --> 02:04:41,348
Would you marry me, Forrest?

1458
02:04:46,604 --> 02:04:47,855
Okay.

1459
02:04:48,898 --> 02:04:50,566
Please take your seats.

1460
02:04:54,404 --> 02:04:56,738
Forrest? It's time to start.

1461
02:05:16,134 --> 02:05:17,718
Hi.

1462
02:05:18,595 --> 02:05:20,095
Your tie.

1463
02:05:32,650 --> 02:05:51,585
Lieutenant Dan.

1464
02:05:52,420 --> 02:05:54,087
Hello, Forrest.

1465
02:05:54,756 --> 02:05:57,424
You got new legs. New legs!

1466
02:05:58,635 --> 02:06:02,429
Yeah. I got new legs. Custom-made.

1467
02:06:03,139 --> 02:06:07,142
Titanium alloy.
It's what they use on the space shuttle.

1468
02:06:10,980 --> 02:06:12,481
Magic legs.

1469
02:06:14,484 --> 02:06:18,862
This is my fiancée, Susan.

1470
02:06:21,658 --> 02:06:25,035
-Lieutenant Dan.
-Hi, Forrest.

1471
02:06:27,121 --> 02:06:30,332
Lieutenant Dan, this is my Jenny.

1472
02:06:30,708 --> 02:06:33,710
Hey. It's nice to meet you finally.

1473
02:06:43,846 --> 02:06:48,016
Do you, Forrest,
take Jenny to be your wife?

1474
02:06:49,894 --> 02:06:54,147
Do you, Jenny,
take Forrest to be your husband?

1475
02:06:55,483 --> 02:06:58,860
And so I pronounce you man and wife.

1476
02:07:29,726 --> 02:07:31,601
-Hey.
-Hey.

1477
02:07:45,283 --> 02:07:47,075
Hey, Forrest.

1478
02:07:52,415 --> 02:07:54,207
Were you scared in Vietnam?

1479
02:07:55,877 --> 02:07:58,211
Yes. Well, l...

1480
02:07:59,547 --> 02:08:01,256
I don't know.

1481
02:08:01,966 --> 02:08:06,928
Sometimes it would stop raining long
enough for the stars to come out.

1482
02:08:10,058 --> 02:08:12,100
And then it was nice.

1483
02:08:15,480 --> 02:08:19,441
It was like just before the sun
goes to bed down on the bayou.

1484
02:08:20,735 --> 02:08:24,613
There was always
a million sparkles on the water.

1485
02:08:26,407 --> 02:08:30,327
Like that mountain lake.
It was so clear, Jenny,

1486
02:08:30,453 --> 02:08:35,040
it looked like there were two skies,
one on top of the other.

1487
02:08:37,585 --> 02:08:40,629
And then, in the desert,
when the sun comes up,

1488
02:08:43,091 --> 02:08:47,260
I couldn't tell where heaven stopped

1489
02:08:47,804 --> 02:08:50,180
and the earth began.

1490
02:08:51,432 --> 02:08:53,308
It was so beautiful.

1491
02:08:58,022 --> 02:09:01,108
I wish I could've been there with you.

1492
02:09:04,195 --> 02:09:05,612
You were.

1493
02:09:16,332 --> 02:09:17,791
I love you.

1494
02:09:22,171 --> 02:09:25,507
You died on a Saturday morning.

1495
02:09:27,218 --> 02:09:30,971
And I had you placed
here under our tree.

1496
02:09:35,852 --> 02:09:40,689
And I had that house of your father's
bulldozed to the ground.

1497
02:09:44,819 --> 02:09:46,486
Mama

1498
02:09:47,572 --> 02:09:52,576
always said that dying was a part of life.

1499
02:09:55,997 --> 02:09:58,331
I sure wish it wasn't.

1500
02:10:01,002 --> 02:10:04,754
Little Forrest is doing just fine.

1501
02:10:06,090 --> 02:10:07,174
But...

1502
02:10:07,425 --> 02:10:10,093
About to start school again soon,

1503
02:10:11,929 --> 02:10:15,724
and I make his breakfast, lunch
and dinner every day.

1504
02:10:17,894 --> 02:10:23,899
I make sure he combs his hair
and brushes his teeth every day.

1505
02:10:27,028 --> 02:10:29,613
Teaching him how to play Ping-Pong.

1506
02:10:30,907 --> 02:10:31,948
Okay.

1507
02:10:32,200 --> 02:10:33,366
He's really good.

1508
02:10:33,451 --> 02:10:35,577
Forrest, you go.

1509
02:10:39,790 --> 02:10:41,374
We fish a lot.

1510
02:10:44,921 --> 02:10:48,381
And every night, we read a book.
He's so smart, Jenny.

1511
02:10:51,636 --> 02:10:53,887
You'd be so proud of him.

1512
02:10:55,598 --> 02:10:57,057
I am.

1513
02:10:58,100 --> 02:11:01,311
He wrote you a letter.

1514
02:11:02,897 --> 02:11:04,940
And he says I can't read it.

1515
02:11:05,066 --> 02:11:08,610
I'm not supposed to,
so I'll just leave it here for you.

1516
02:11:24,669 --> 02:11:26,002
Jenny,

1517
02:11:31,801 --> 02:11:35,011
I don't know if Mama was right,

1518
02:11:36,347 --> 02:11:37,847
or if it's Lieutenant Dan.

1519
02:11:37,974 --> 02:11:40,559
I don't know

1520
02:11:40,643 --> 02:11:45,146
if we each have a destiny,

1521
02:11:47,191 --> 02:11:52,320
or if we're all just floating around
accidental-like on a breeze.

1522
02:11:56,826 --> 02:11:58,660
But I think

1523
02:12:00,538 --> 02:12:02,330
maybe it's both.

1524
02:12:06,669 --> 02:12:09,546
Maybe both is happening
at the same time.

1525
02:12:15,678 --> 02:12:17,679
But I miss you, Jenny.

1526
02:12:24,061 --> 02:12:28,481
lf there's anything you need,
I won't be far away.

1527
02:13:03,768 --> 02:13:06,728
Here's your bus. Okay.

1528
02:13:08,397 --> 02:13:11,733
Hey. I know this.

1529
02:13:11,859 --> 02:13:14,736
I'm gonna show that
for show-and-tell because

1530
02:13:14,862 --> 02:13:17,530
Grandma used to read it to you.

1531
02:13:17,615 --> 02:13:19,741
My favorite book.

1532
02:13:23,079 --> 02:13:24,579
Here we are.

1533
02:13:24,747 --> 02:13:26,206
Okay.

1534
02:13:27,917 --> 02:13:29,417
Here you go.

1535
02:13:34,298 --> 02:13:36,800
Hey, Forrest, don't...

1536
02:13:40,262 --> 02:13:43,973
-I wanted to tell you, I love you.
-I love you, too, Daddy.

1537
02:13:45,976 --> 02:13:48,770
I'll be right here when you get back.

1538
02:13:53,317 --> 02:13:56,569
You understand this is
the bus to school, now, don't you?

1539
02:13:56,654 --> 02:14:00,198
Of course, and you are Dorothy Harris,
and I'm Forrest Gump.

